    "fullText": "When the Congress Avenue Bridge in downtown Austin was renovated in 1980, engineers accidentally created the perfect bat habitat: deep crevices in the bridge's underside that stay warm and dark. Mexican free-tailed bats moved in by the hundreds of thousands, and the colony now numbers around 1.5 million during peak season. Every evening from March to November, the bats emerge at sunset in a swirling black cloud that can take up to 45 minutes to fully exit the bridge. They consume an estimated 10,000 to 30,000 pounds of insects every single night, providing free pest control for the city. Austinites initially wanted the bats removed, but Bat Conservation International launched an education campaign that turned public opinion around. Now the nightly emergence is one of Austin's top tourist attractions, with crowds gathering on the bridge and along the lakeshore to watch.",
