    "fullText": "The Battle of the Alamo in 1836, where roughly 200 Texian defenders held out for 13 days against thousands of Mexican soldiers under General Santa Anna, is one of the most mythologized events in American history. What nobody tells you is that the Alamo chapel, the iconic building everyone recognizes, is genuinely tiny -- about 75 feet long and 62 feet wide. It sits incongruously in the heart of modern downtown San Antonio, surrounded by hotels, restaurants, and a Ripley's Believe It or Not museum. The larger compound where the actual battle took place has been mostly built over by the city. For decades, the site was managed by the Daughters of the Republic of Texas before being designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2015. Visitors routinely express shock at how small the chapel is compared to its enormous cultural footprint. Remember the Alamo, sure, but also remember to adjust your expectations.",
