    "title": "The Skyscraper a Plane Actually Hit (and It Stayed Standing)",
    "summary": "In 1945, a B-25 bomber got lost in fog and slammed into the 79th floor of the Empire State Building. Fourteen people died, but the building barely flinched and was open for business two days later.",
    "fullText": "On July 28, 1945, a B-25 Mitchell bomber piloted by Lieutenant Colonel William Franklin Smith Jr. became disoriented in thick fog over Manhattan and crashed into the north side of the Empire State Building between the 78th and 80th floors. The impact killed 11 people in the building and all three on the plane. One of the plane's engines shot completely through the building and landed on a nearby rooftop. A severed elevator cable sent operator Betty Lou Oliver plunging 75 stories in her elevator car, which she survived, setting the Guinness World Record for the longest survived elevator fall. Despite a massive fire and the loss of 14 lives, the building's structural integrity was barely affected, and most offices reopened within two days. The incident is frequently cited in discussions about why the World Trade Center collapsed on 9/11, though the physics of the two events were vastly different.",
