    "title": "The Shore Where a Hindenburg Fell from the Sky",
    "summary": "On May 6, 1937, the German airship Hindenburg burst into flames while landing at Lakehurst, New Jersey. The disaster killed 36 people and single-handedly ended the age of passenger airships.",
    "fullText": "The Hindenburg, the largest flying structure ever built at 804 feet long, was attempting to dock at Naval Air Station Lakehurst in New Jersey on May 6, 1937, when it suddenly caught fire and was consumed in about 37 seconds. Thirty-five of the 97 people aboard died, along with one ground crew member. Radio reporter Herbert Morrison's live broadcast, including his anguished cry 'Oh, the humanity!' became one of the most famous pieces of audio in history. The cause of the fire remains debated to this day, with theories ranging from static electricity igniting leaking hydrogen to sabotage. The disaster effectively killed the passenger airship industry overnight, even though 62 of the 97 people on board actually survived. The site at Lakehurst is now a National Historic Landmark, with a small chain marking the exact spot where the burning airship hit the ground.",
