    "title": "The Donner Party Got Stuck Right Here",
    "summary": "In the winter of 1846-47, the Donner Party became snowbound near Truckee, California. Of the 87 pioneers, 48 survived -- some by resorting to cannibalism of those who had already died.",
    "fullText": "In October 1846, a group of 87 American pioneers led by George Donner became trapped by early snowfall in the Sierra Nevada mountains near what is now Donner Lake, California. The group had taken an ill-advised shortcut called the Hastings Cutoff, which added weeks to their journey and left them fatally behind schedule. As winter set in with up to 22 feet of snow, the party's food ran out, and some members of the group resorted to eating the flesh of those who had died from starvation and exposure. Of the 87 members of the party, only 48 survived to reach California. The ordeal became one of the most notorious episodes in the history of westward expansion. Donner Memorial State Park now occupies the site, and the Pioneer Monument's base stands exactly 22 feet high, marking the depth of the snow during that terrible winter. Interstate 80 now passes over Donner Pass, and every winter, modern travelers get stuck in snowstorms along the same stretch of road.",
    "category": "history",
