    "lng": -116.8256,
    "title": "The Hottest Place on the Planet Is Down There",
    "summary": "Death Valley holds the record for the highest air temperature ever reliably recorded on Earth: 134 degrees Fahrenheit on July 10, 1913. It is also the lowest point in North America at 282 feet below sea level.",
    "fullText": "Death Valley, straddling the California-Nevada border, is a land of superlatives. It holds the record for the highest reliably recorded air temperature on Earth: 134 degrees Fahrenheit (56.7 degrees Celsius) at Furnace Creek on July 10, 1913. Badwater Basin, at 282 feet below sea level, is the lowest point in North America. The valley is also one of the driest places on the continent, averaging less than 2 inches of rainfall per year. Despite these extreme conditions, the valley supports a surprising diversity of life, including the Devils Hole pupfish, which exists in a single water-filled cavern and is one of the rarest animals on Earth. Death Valley got its name from a group of gold rush pioneers who became lost crossing it in 1849; one person died, and as the survivors finally escaped through a mountain pass, one reportedly turned around and said 'Goodbye, Death Valley.' The name stuck.",
    "category": "nature",
    "year": "ongoing",
    "imageUrl": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d8/Badwater_Basin_from_Dante%27s_View_overlook.jpg/1280px-Badwater_Basin_from_Dante%27s_View_overlook.jpg",
    "videoUrl": "",
    "location": "Death Valley, California"
