    "id": "misc-007",
    "lat": 43.8791,
    "lng": -103.4591,
    "title": "Mount Rushmore Was Supposed to Have Full Bodies",
    "summary": "The original plan for Mount Rushmore included the presidents carved down to the waist. Sculptor Gutzon Borglum ran out of funding and suitable rock, so we got heads only. He also died before finishing.",
    "fullText": "Gutzon Borglum's original vision for Mount Rushmore was far more ambitious than what we see today. The initial design called for the four presidents to be carved from head to waist, with George Washington depicted emerging from the mountain in a dramatic pose. Budget constraints and the quality of the granite kept forcing Borglum to scale back his plans. Jefferson's face was originally started on Washington's right side, but the rock was too crumbly, so the partially carved face had to be dynamited off and restarted on the other side. Borglum also planned a Hall of Records, a grand chamber carved into the canyon behind the faces to store important American documents, but only a 70-foot tunnel was completed before work stopped. Borglum died in March 1941, and his son Lincoln finished up the remaining details before work permanently ceased later that year. The project took 14 years and cost just under $1 million, and remarkably, not a single worker died during construction despite the daily use of dynamite on a sheer granite cliff.",
    "category": "landmark",
    "year": "1927 - 1941",
    "imageUrl": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Dean_Franklin_-_06.04.03_Mount_Rushmore_Monument_%28by-sa%29-3_new.jpg/1280px-Dean_Franklin_-_06.04.03_Mount_Rushmore_Monument_%28by-sa%29-3_new.jpg",
