    "title": "The Muscle Beach That Launched a Billion Gym Memberships",
    "summary": "Santa Monica's Muscle Beach, and its successor Venice Beach, became the global epicenter of bodybuilding culture in the 1930s-70s. Arnold Schwarzenegger, the governor of California, used to pump iron here in a speedo.",
    "fullText": "The original Muscle Beach in Santa Monica became a gathering spot for acrobats, gymnasts, and weightlifters in the 1930s, attracting crowds who came to watch impossibly fit people perform feats of strength on the sand. When Santa Monica shut down its beach fitness area in 1959 after a scandal, the bodybuilding community migrated south to Venice Beach, where Gold's Gym became the epicenter of competitive bodybuilding. Arnold Schwarzenegger trained at Gold's Gym Venice in the 1970s, and the documentary 'Pumping Iron' (1977) turned the gym into a global landmark. The outdoor weight pen at Venice Beach, known as 'The Pit,' became the most photographed open-air gym in the world. Muscle Beach Venice is still an active workout area, drawing fitness enthusiasts from around the globe who want to lift weights in the same salty ocean air as Arnold. The cultural impact of these two beaches on global fitness culture is genuinely difficult to overstate.",
