    "title": "The Oldest Capital City in America Barely Anyone Visits",
    "summary": "Santa Fe, New Mexico was founded in 1610, a full decade before the Pilgrims landed at Plymouth Rock. It is the oldest state capital in the United States and sits at 7,199 feet elevation, the highest of any state capital.",
    "fullText": "Santa Fe was established as the capital of the Spanish colony of Nuevo Mexico in 1610, making it the oldest capital city in what is now the United States. The Palace of the Governors on the central plaza has been in continuous use as a government building since 1610, predating the Mayflower's arrival by a decade. At 7,199 feet above sea level, Santa Fe is also the highest state capital in the country, which gives it a climate that surprises visitors who expect New Mexico to be uniformly hot and flat. The city receives about 15 inches of snow per year and has a thriving ski area just 16 miles from the downtown plaza. Santa Fe is also one of the world's great art markets, with over 250 galleries in a city of just 88,000 people. The city's adobe architecture is not just aesthetic -- a municipal ordinance requires that all buildings in the historic district conform to the Pueblo Revival or Territorial Revival architectural styles, giving the entire city center a unified, ancient appearance.",
