    "id": "atl-corridor-017",
    "lat": 32.7555,
    "lng": -97.3308,
    "title": "The Stockyards That Refused to Die",
    "summary": "The Fort Worth Stockyards still drive cattle through the streets twice a day, making it the only place in the world with a daily cattle drive down a city street. This has been happening since 1866.",
    "fullText": "Fort Worth earned the nickname 'Cowtown' in the 1860s when it became a major stop on the Chisholm Trail, the route cowboys used to drive millions of Texas longhorn cattle north to Kansas railheads. The Fort Worth Stockyards, once the largest livestock market in the Southwest, processed millions of head of cattle. When the meatpacking industry moved on, the stockyards reinvented themselves as a tourist attraction and entertainment district. Today, visitors can watch a genuine cattle drive twice daily at 11:30 AM and 4:00 PM as a herd of Texas longhorns is driven down East Exchange Avenue by cowboys on horseback. It is the only twice-daily cattle drive in the world conducted on a city street. The stockyards district also contains Billy Bob's Texas, which bills itself as the world's largest honky-tonk at 127,000 square feet and can hold 6,000 people. The venue has hosted concerts by everyone from Willie Nelson to Merle Haggard to Motley Crue.",
    "category": "culture",
    "year": "1866 - present",
