    "id": "mw-tx-004",
    "lat": 32.3487,
    "lng": -95.3011,
    "title": "The Town That Grows Sweet Potatoes and Celebrates Them Hard",
    "summary": "Gilmer, Texas hosts the East Texas Yamboree every October, a festival dedicated entirely to the sweet potato. There is a yam queen, yam pie contests, and a yam parade.",
    "fullText": "Since 1935, the small town of Gilmer in East Texas has thrown the East Texas Yamboree, a multi-day festival honoring the sweet potato. The event features a Yam Queen pageant, yam pie baking competitions, livestock shows, a carnival, and a grand parade through downtown. Gilmer sits in Upshur County, which was once one of the top sweet potato producing regions in the state. The festival routinely draws tens of thousands of visitors to a town with a population of about 5,000. Locals insist on calling them yams, even though what they grow are technically sweet potatoes. The Yamboree is one of the oldest continuously running festivals in Texas.",
    "category": "culture",
