    "title": "The Hand-Dug Swimming Pool of Balmorhea",
    "summary": "Balmorhea State Park has a spring-fed swimming pool that covers 1.3 acres and stays a constant 72-76 degrees year-round. It is the largest spring-fed pool in the world.",
    "fullText": "Balmorhea State Park in west Texas is home to the San Solomon Springs, which pump out 15 to 26 million gallons of water daily into the world's largest spring-fed swimming pool. The pool covers 1.3 acres and reaches depths of 25 feet. The Civilian Conservation Corps built the pool walls and surrounding structures in the 1930s during the Depression. The water stays a constant 72 to 76 degrees Fahrenheit year-round. Two endangered species, the Comanche Springs pupfish and the Pecos gambusia, live in the pool alongside swimmers. Scuba divers use the pool for training because of its remarkable clarity and depth.",
    "category": "nature",
    "year": "1936",
    "imageUrl": "",
